Form Validation in React

Definition:
Form validation in React is the process of checking user input before submitting a form to ensure that the entered data is correct and complete.

Simple Example
JavaScript
import React, { useState } from "react";

function App() {
  const [name, setName] = useState("");

  const validate = () => {
    if (name === "") {
      alert("Name is required");
    } else {
      alert("Form Submitted");
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="text"
        placeholder="Enter Name"
        onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
      />
      <button onClick={validate}>Submit</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
Output

If the textbox is empty → "Name is required"

If a name is entered → "Form Submitted"

Explanation

useState() stores the input value.

onChange updates the state.

validate() checks whether the field is empty.

If empty, an error message is shown; otherwise, the form is submitted.

Short Exam Definition

Form validation in React is used to verify user input and ensure that valid data is entered before form submission. ✅

